25|$|IBM's Human Ability and Accessibility Center, {{with the}} IBM Virtual Universe Community, {{developed}} a Web-based interface for Second Life {{that can be}} accessed with a <b>screen</b> <b>reader.</b> This client provides basic navigation, communication, and perception functions using hotkeys.|$|E
25|$|In {{the face}} of <b>screen</b> <b>reader</b> software, braille usage has declined. However, because it teaches {{spelling}} and punctuation, braille education remains important for developing reading skills among {{blind and visually impaired}} children, and braille literacy correlates with higher employment rates.|$|E
25|$|Another type of <b>screen</b> <b>reader</b> is Apple VoiceOver. This {{software}} is provided {{free of charge}} on all Apple devices. Apple VoiceOver includes the option to magnify the screen, control the keyboard, and provide verbal descriptions to describe what is happening on the screen. There are thirty languages to select from. It also {{has the capacity to}} read aloud file content, as well as web pages, E-mail messages, and word processing files.|$|E
